        <h2>Real Reform Happens Here</h2>
        <p>In Arizona, mass incarceration isn't distant—it's a daily crisis. ADCRR's annual budget tops $1.77 billion, yet the agency spent $30 million defending constitutional violations and $2.4 million in contempt fines for ignoring court orders. Over 33,000 people have been incarcerated into known Eighth Amendment violations since June 2022. Praxis Initiative addresses this urgency by combining credible messenger advocacy with rigorous policy research. When we testify at the Capitol, legislators listen because we've lived on the yards where these policies play out.</p>
        <p>Our bipartisan approach sets us apart. We work across party lines because caging human beings isn't partisan—it's moral. In 2025, we co-sponsored SB 1507 with Justice Action Network, CPAC's Nolan Center for Justice, and FAMM, earning support from both progressive Democrats and conservative Republicans. This is the Praxis model: find common ground where freedom expands, hold firm where dignity is non-negotiable.</p>
        <p>The results speak volumes. Since 2020, our advocacy impacted dozens of legislative proposals, trained hundreds of returning citizens as advocates, and established the first independent prison oversight body in Arizona's 57-year history. But we measure success in human terms: the mother who can visit her son without arbitrary visitation denials, the artist who publishes poetry from Perryville Prison, the advocate who now chairs a state commission.</p>
